		<title>The Passive-Aggressive Guide to Book Gifting</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/ThePassiveVoice/~3/1DFfEEzRYOY/</link>
		<comments>http://www.thepassivevoice.com/12/2014/the-passive-aggressive-guide-to-book-gifting/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2014 19:00:51 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Passive Guy]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Books in General]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.thepassivevoice.com/?p=59001</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[From The Toast: Hamlet, by William Shakespeare The perfect gift for: Your mom What you’re really saying: “Your new boyfriend is not my dad and I’m going to make things very difficult for you.” . . . . The Odyssey, by Homer The perfect gift for: Your boyfriend What you’re really saying: “You’re always late, and I [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>From The Toast:</p>
<blockquote><p><strong><em>Hamlet</em></strong><em>,</em> by William Shakespeare<br />
<strong>The perfect gift for:</strong> Your mom<br />
<strong>What you’re really saying:</strong> “Your new boyfriend is not my dad and I’m going to make things very difficult for you.”</p>
<p>. . . .</p>
<p><strong><em>The Odyssey</em></strong>, by Homer<br />
<strong>The perfect gift for:</strong> Your boyfriend<br />
<strong>What you’re really saying:</strong> “You’re always late, and I have other options.”</p>
<p>. . . .</p>
<p><strong><em>Life in a Medieval Village</em></strong>, by Frances Gies and Joseph Gies<br />
<strong>The perfect gift for:</strong> Your new intern<br />
<strong>What you’re really saying:</strong> “Welcome to my fiefdom, peasant.”</p></blockquote>
